Every generation inherits the budget choices of the last â and the consequences of pretending they were inevitable.

If we want real change, it doesnât start with slogans or personalities. It starts with teaching the next generation to question why endless foreign aid is treated as untouchable while problems at home are framed as too expensive, too complicated, or too divisive to solve.

Crumbling infrastructure. Student debt. Housing shortages. Healthcare gaps. Communities stretched thin. None of these are abstract. Theyâre daily realities, paid for with the same tax dollars that flow overseas with far less debate.

This isnât isolationism. Itâs prioritization. A country that canât take care of its own people shouldnât pretend generosity abroad substitutes for responsibility at home. Strong nations are built inward first â through stability, opportunity, and trust â not through permanent financial commitments that voters never meaningfully approve.

Inspiring the next generation means teaching them that budgets are moral documents. That every dollar sent elsewhere is a choice not to spend it here. And that questioning those choices isnât unpatriotic â itâs democratic.

Change wonât come from the same talking points recycled every election cycle.
It will come from young people who refuse to accept that âthis is just how it works.â

Because the future belongs to those willing to redraw priorities â and insist that serving your own people isnât selfish, itâs foundational.

For context, Avengers: Endgame clocked in at just over three hours, a length that was once viewed as a gamble for mainstream theaters. A near four hour runtime suggests the Russo Brothers may be stacking multiple character arcs, crossover threads, and long term MCU setup into one event scale film. Nothing has been confirmed, but even the rumor alone points to Doomsday being positioned less as a standard sequel and more as a full scale narrative centerpiece.
